Interview Project Submission (Business Owners Policies)¶

Nationwide Insurance Business Insights Team Daran Thach (job applicant) 6.29.22

The main objective is to discover the industry segments trending higher in Loss Ratios. From the data, propose a hypothesis why, and recommend a solution for it. In the investigation of the data, consider the following questions:

  • Are certain segments performing markedly poorer than others? If so, hypothesize to why and propose a recommendation to fix.
  • Is there a common story inherent in the data? What does this story tell at a high level? What should we do as a result?
  • Are there areas or segments that produce strange results?
  • What additional data do you wish you had?

Summary of hypotheses and recommendations¶

  1. There is a statistically significant relationship between loss incurred and loss ratio. As shown in the results below, there is a significant correlation between incurred loss and loss ratio, holding other variables to a normalized scale. Across all commercial lines, loss ratios have trended lower. The business lines underperforming in this metric are retail and warehouse segments, with habitational and food service segments performing better.

Recommendation: Monitor loss ratio as a function of differentiated claim type (liability, workers comp, property). This allows one to drill down which specific claims are incurring the heavier incurred loss. Underwrite coverage to adjust premiums up for retail and warehouse if seeking higher profitability. Consider raising deductibles for more frequent claims.¶

  1. COVID-19 related factors possibly influenced the recent loss ratio performance. Without having more data such as reasons for new claim reasons (injury, accidents, lawsuits, property damage), we cannot correlate the magnitude of pandemic response to loss ratio. Visually, new claims did seem to rise with the brunt of COVID's onset in the spring of 2020, as shown in the 'new claims' chart of dashboard below:

https://public.tableau.com/views/TrendsforBOPData2019-Present/Dashboard1?:language=en-US&:display_count=n&:origin=viz_share_link

Recommend tracking reasons on new claims for added analysis. Consider underwriting premium increases, especially on casualty retail, should uncertainties last longer than expected. Expect demand to return as clients become more risk aware in the aftermath of the pandemic.¶

  1. Monetary inflation influenced the downtrend of policies carried in 2022. It is likely that the forces of inflation and the higher cost of doing business led to decreased policy carrying. This is reflected in a few ways: a) insurer is decreasing its exposure to clients, b) businesses are cancelling or trimming down their policies, or c) business are closing due to rising costs. As an experiment, we consider the chart below, which shows a positive correlation between PCE (personal consumption expenditures) to the amount of commercial policies carried:

https://public.tableau.com/views/PersonalConsumerExpendituresPCEpricevsCommercialPoliciesCarried/Sheet2?:language=en-US&:display_count=n&:origin=viz_share_link

Recommend periodic monitoring of loss ratio figures. Maintain underwriting preference towards a higher premium, while being aware of deflationary risk. If new claims incur higher losses, be flexible by adjusting premiums up.¶

  1. Weather events losses are discretely hidden in the findings. The dataset likely reflects weather event-related claims. When Texas had a statewide power outage from the ill-prepared winter freeze, this may have led to the spike of losses in 2021. Recommend analysis of property damage claims. Weather data centers can help provide real-time information to reduce extent of property damage. Coverages need to profitably share the amount of risk taken, but build trust with clients.

Recommend reducing the coverage differences for natural disasters and severe weather events. Coordinate alerting efforts with climate data centers. In times of weather distress, mitigate risk through diligent communication. Stay transparent in justifying premium adjustments or restrictions.¶

  1. Cybersecurity breach losses are discretely hidden in the findings. Cybersecurity crime is becoming more commonplace for commercial entities, large or small. Underwriting should reflect the extent of damage potential for firms possessing large amounts of sensitive data.

Recommend analysis of property damage claims and underwrite according to amount of personal data stored. Stay transparent in justifying premium adjustments or restrictions.¶

Background¶

An insurance company's loss ratio shows the relationship between incurred losses and earned premiums. Insurance companies with very high loss ratios may need to raise premiums to stay solvent and ensure their ability to pay future claims. A very low loss ratio means that consumers are paying too much for the benefit received. A higher loss ratio means lower profits for the insurance company and is, therefore, a problem for underwriters and investors alike. Underwriters and investors use the loss ratio for various purposes. IL/EP *100 = Loss Ratio %.

High LRs risk being unable to meet future liability payments. Underwriters are particularly interested in the loss ratio. When the claims loss ratio is too high, either the premiums must rise or certain insured groups must be denied coverage. In the insurance industry, this is referred to as a hardening of the market. Investors are also interested in the loss ratio. They may use the combined loss ratio (both losses and expenses) as one of many metrics to compare insurance companies for investment decisions.

  1. What are the inputs and outputs for a forecast? Time series (dates from 2019-2022), both structured (continuous numeric, categorical), partially unstructured data (years in business). Forecasting a time series may yield tremendous commercial value. Consider LR for multivariate time series forecasting.
  2. Are you working on a regression or classification predictive modeling problem? Regression & Descriptive Models.
  3. Are you working on a univariate or multivariate time series problem? Multivariate.
  4. Do you require a single-step or a multi-step forecast? Multi-step to compare against numeric variables, then
  5. Do you require a static or a dynamically updated model? Static for purposes of project.

1a. Input considerations¶

Numeric variables

Does the numeric explanatory variables affect the response variable? Linear regression is a good model to consider. The coefficient of determination (R squared) describes the overall relationship between the independent variables X (deductibles, policies in force, earned premium) and the dependent variable Y (loss ratio). The regression coefficient (b) determines the overall positive/negative relationship. We need to find which variables can best explain the dependent variable. Our inference on the data parameters using hypothesis testing is:

H0. There is no significant relationship between the independent predictor (X1, X2, X3...) and dependent variable (Y); b=0. HA. There is a significant relationship between the independent predictor (X1, X2, X3...) and dependent variable (Y); b !=0.

Categorical variables

Categorical var: How are the segments related to the response variable, and to what extent? Typically we need to change the granularity of the variable to provide more generalizable results for LR. For at least one variable, may change granularity to fit into regression. For categorical independent variable industry, can assess trends visually distributed continuous as it relates to dependent variable, loss ratio.

Observation¶

DEDUCTIBLE_BUCKET, PIF, EP, IL, NEW_CLAIMS, BUILDING_COUNT, BLDG_COVALIMIT, & BLDG_COVBLIMIT have varying scales, non-normal distribution and large std deviations.

Recommend normalize data for distribution to perform linear regression model. This rescales the data from the original range so that all values are within the range of 0 and 1. This prevents the model from favoring values with a larger scale.

Normalization can be useful, and even required in some machine learning algorithms when your TS data has input values with differing scales. It may be required for algorithms, like k-Nearest neighbors, and Linear Regression. Use normalization when you dont know the distribution of your data or you know it is not Gaussian.

jet= plt.get_cmap('jet')
colors = iter(jet(np.linspace(0,1,10)))
 
def correlation(scaleddate_df,variables, n_rows, n_cols):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(14,9))

    for i, var in enumerate(variables):
        ax = fig.add_subplot(n_rows,n_cols,i+1)
        asset = scaleddate_df.loc[:,var]
        ax.scatter(scaleddate_df['LOSS_RATIO'], asset, color = next(colors))
        ax.set_xlabel("LOSS_RATIO")
        ax.set_ylabel("{}".format(var))
        ax.set_title(var +" VS LR")
    fig.tight_layout() 
    plt.show()
# Use all variables except the last column, 'lOSS_RATIO'.
variables = scaleddate_df.columns[0:9]
correlation(scaleddate_df, variables, 4,3)

Observation.¶

Per Pearson correlation coefficient, the best linear relationship between 2 variables takes on -1 or 1, where 0 indicates no linear correlation. After performing the correlation plot, incurred loss sits close to 1. All other variables are very close to 0, thus no correlation. After we run the correlation to the loss ratio, we find that that incurred loss is very positively correlated to loss ratio (0.89), and may be used as a predictor.

3.1 Split the dataset into a train and test set.¶

In forecasting time series, we assume that the trend to be analyzed is either linear or exponential over time. This assumption can induce a model that is overly robust, and even wrong if the time series changes over time (i.e., a harsh winter causing power grid blackout). To see local pattern changes, we consider MAPE (mean absolute percentage error).

3.2 Fit a candidate approach on the training dataset.¶

In LR we basically find which line best represents variable y from variable (X1,X2,X3...). It is quantified by the ordinary least squares, which chooses the regression line that minimizes the sum of squares of differences b/t independent to predicted variable.

In [57]:

                 "DEDUCTIBLE_BUCKET", "DWP", "PIF", "NEW_CLAIMS", "IL", "EP"]]

lr.fit(x_train, y_train)

3.3 Make predictions on the test set directly.¶

3.4 Calculate a metric to compare predictions to expected values.¶

After linear regression, we can infer the quality of the linear regression. Checking the residual terms (error terms of independent variables) can ensure autocorrelation is not violated. We evaluate TS regression forecast with MAE (Mean Absolute Error) and MAPE (Mean Absolute Percentage Error).

MAPE tells you how wrong your forecasts are percentage-wise. I like it because, in a way, it is equivalent to accuracy metric in classification problems.

In [59]:
# Predict 'LOSS RATIO' using test variables, then evaluate regression with metric.
## Compute mean absolute error of predicted/real loss ratio.

lossratio_pred = lr.predict(x_test)

lossratio_mae = sum(abs(lossratio_pred - test["LOSS_RATIO"].values)) / test.shape[0]

print(lossratio_mae)

0.028770152850382185
In [60]:
# Calculate mean absolute percentage error.
lossratio_mape = sum(abs(lossratio_pred - y_test)) / test.shape[0] * 100
lossratio_mape
Out[60]:
2.8770152850382185

Observation.¶

We resulted in a MAE value of 0.029 (MAPE 2.9%) which means these forecasts are 97.1% accurate. In scaled terms, this is the average diff between predicted and actual loss ratio. Now we visualize the error terms.

3.5 Find associations between categorical and target variable.¶

We are interested in how categorical independent variables (industry segment) relates to a normally distributed continuous (interval or ratio level) dependent variable. We want to see how the loss ratio changes per industry, and to what extent?

We apply groupby method and pass it in a column, to split the data into relevant groups, based on the criteria passed in. The reason for applying this method is to break a big data analysis problem into manageable parts. Then we can perform operations on the individual parts and put them back together. While the apply and combine steps occur separately, Pandas abstracts this and makes it appear as though it was a single step.

4. Summarize model for recommendations.¶

We explored data from a time series of numerical and categorical variables of commercial insurance data, from mid-2019 to mid-2022. Our target variable loss ratio, a percentage of incurred loss to earned premium. In this data, several numeric variables were found to vary in scales and type. We normalized to this data and then calculated linear regression from trained data, relating independent variables, discovering a high correlation between loss incurred and loss ratio.

We also looked at categorical industry segment, and upon modeling time series and plots, discovered an overall downtrend in loss ratios over time. As the majority of segments are under 70%, this implies healthy profitability. The poorer performing segments are retail, warehouse (profit < 45%). The higher performing segments are in auto and food service, habitational, office and service (profit >45%).
